> When it comes to Mexican food, tacos typically get all the glory. In our opinion, flautas are an unsung dinner hero. They're technically just crispy, rolled-up tacos—but they're really so much more than that. Seriously, what could be better than warm, crunchy tortillas stuffed with all kinds of delicious fillings? Ours boast stewed and mashed black beans, diced poblano, and jalapeño-flecked pepper jack. They're then pan-fried until deeply golden and topped with guacamole, pico de gallo, sour cream, and hot sauce.

Wash and dry all produce.

Finely dice @roma tomato{1}(finely diced). Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}(thinly sliced). Halve @lime{1}.

In a #small bowl{}, combine tomato, scallions, a big squeeze of lime juice, and a drizzle of @olive oil{1%tsp}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Halve, peel, and thinly slice @yellow onion{1}(thinly sliced). Core, deseed, and dice @poblano pepper{1}(diced into ½-inch pieces). Drain @black beans{13.4%ounce} over a separate small bowl, reserving liquid.

== Filling ==

Heat a drizzle of @vegetable oil{1%tsp} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add onion and poblano; cook until just softened, ~{5-6%minutes}.

Add @southwest spice blend{1%tablespoon} and half the beans (you'll use the rest in the next step). Cook, stirring, until fragrant and warmed through, ~{2-3%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper. Remove pan from heat.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @vegetable oil{1%tsp} in a #small pot{} over medium-high heat. Add remaining beans and cook, stirring, until slightly softened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Add ¼ cup reserved bean liquid (½ cup for 4 servings). Simmer until warmed through, ~{1-2%minutes}. Reduce heat to low and stir in @butter{1%tablespoon}.

Remove pot from heat; mash beans with a #potato masher{} or fork until mostly smooth. Season with plenty of salt and pepper.

== Assembly ==

Spread @flour tortillas{6} with mashed beans. Place a small amount of filling on one half of each tortilla, then sprinkle with @pepper jack cheese{1/2%cup}.

Roll up tortillas, starting with filled sides, to create flautas. Place seam sides down on a #plate{}.

Wash out pan used for filling. Heat a large drizzle of @vegetable oil{2%tablespoons} in same pan over medium-high heat. Add flautas seam sides down.

Cook, carefully turning so flautas stay intact, until golden brown and crispy, ~{1-2%minutes} per side.

> Tip: Work in batches if necessary and watch carefully to avoid burning.

Divide flautas between plates and top with @guacamole{4%tablespoons}, pico de gallo, and @sour cream{4%tablespoons}. Alternatively, serve with toppings on the side.